Modeling Video Game Sales¶

Executive summary - The importance of games¶

This document details the analysis and evaluation of the profitability of video game genres in a diverse suite of geographic regions. This project utilizes the Kagel 'Video Game Sales' dataset to model the preference of gamers based on historical game sales [1].

The scale of the video game industry can at times be difficult to grasp. With a catelog of titles dating back to the classic Atari pong, the video game industry has ballooned to \$155 billion in 2020, with expectations of the industry surging to \\$200 billion in 2023 [2]. As the scale of the video game industry continues to increase, so too is the ferocity of competition between developers aiming at becoming the next major gaming phenomina. With highly sucessful titles like 'Fortnite' generating revenues exceess of \$300 million in April 2020 alone, developers are facing the problem of increasing pressure from investors to find the next highly successful gaming genre [3].

This project aims to better understand game sales (based on game genre) by utilizing historcal game sales of similar style games. The purpose of this project is to assist developers in better understanding how their prospective games will perform in a given sales market, by leveraging historical data from a simlar sales region. This paper proposes a predictive model to simulate the performance of future games in a given genre. The project seeks to produce the following key results: predict posterior values from game sales through both simuation and credible intervals, validate if the model results agree with historical observations made.

Introduction - Problem Statement and Summary Findings¶

To forcast the success of future games in various geographical regions, this project utilizes the Kaggle 'Video Game Sales' dataset to model the preference of gamers based on historical game sales [1]. With emerging new consoles from Playstation and Microsoft (recently released in 2020), developers are now presented with the opportunity to captialize on new and emerging platforms still in their infancy. This opportunity highlights a need to provide developers with a model to better understand potential target markets.

In reviewing the Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) for popular genres by region sales, there are clear preferntial differences. While European and North American gamers perfer action titles and shooters, Japanese players perfer role-rlaying games signficantly more. This report will begin by presenting developers with a suite of frequenist models to visualize how game sales are impacted by genre. Following which, readers will be presented with a Bayesian model to simulate and predict the success of a game based on the prior distrubtion of genre's historical sales from a sister sales region. Here success is defined as a game that recieves a minimum of \1 million units sold.

A suite of frequentist models are presented, with the intent of producing a mean estimate for each game genre's sales. To achieve this, a bootstrap point estimate of each given genre's sales for each sales region is computed. Repeating this simulation provides readers with insight into the true mean for the given genre statistic. Given the high dimensionality of this dataset presented in the EDA, a cognostics of the top 4 fastest selling game genres for each geographic region and 4 most profitable gaming genres irrespective of region, are presented as well.

Following this, the paper presents readers with a Bayesian probabalistic model that (for various sample sizes from the dataset) computes a posterior distribution for a given game genre being a comercial success. Here the paper defines a commerical success as a title that recieves a minimum of 1 million copies sold. Production of this model requires a one-hot-encoding of region sales, followed by a stratified sample from each region subdivided into genre to evaluate the accuracy of the posterior. A prior distribution is established by leveraging known sales values from a similar sister sales region. Specifically, the paper attempts to predict European platfrom game sales in the mid 1990s, by utilizing North American Platform sales data from the previous five years as the prior distribution.

The paper attempts to address the following key results: to better understand the relationship between game sales and their coresponding genre. To better understand how game genres drive sales in a given region, and showcase how customer purchase preferences have evolved over time. Inform publishers on what games will likely succeed based on their projected genre grouping. Each of these key results is aimed towards optimizing publisher investments, potentially avoiding occurances where game publishers invest in a video game title that will likely underperform.

# Computes the sum of all null value entries within a given dataframe
# @param df The dataframe to analyize 
# @return column/nullVal key pairs as Series
def getNullCounts(df):

    nullVals = {} # Dictionary records the column and null value summation
    
    for col in vgsales.columns:
        nullVals[col] = df[col].isnull().sum()
    
    return pd.Series(nullVals, index=nullVals.keys())

Data Models¶

The exploratory data analysis of the Kagel 'Video Game Sales' dataset has reinforced the fact that consumer preferences vary significantly between geographic sales regions. Furthermore, analysis of the dataset suggests that these non-uniform purchase decisions are likely infuenced further by market maturity, product saturation and regional publisher dominance. These insights underpin the need for more formal analytical methods to properly model profitabilty and growth of game genres within all sales regions. The following section will describe the use of frequentist and bayesian models to better understand the problem of current and future game genre growth.

Understanding Mean Estimates of gaming genres per-region.¶

We begin by performing a nonparametric resampling of genre sales. A bootstrap resampling process was selected in order to better understand and estimate the mean sales performance of game genres in their respective sales region. However, given the relatively small number of unique per-genre titles that are particularly prevelant in earlier years of the dataset, the use of a bootstrap resampling process may result in potentially biased values. Drawing upon the central limit theorem (CLT), we see that each genre distribution appears normally distributed as expected. The resulting Q-Q plots confirm this. However, there do appear to be a few bootstrap distributions which do not quite appear Normally distributed. For instance, Global Sports genre sales appear to slightly deviate from a Normal distribution and indicate a fair amount of skewness.

A valuable insight to be made is the comparative difference in mean genre sales between two seperate regions. For instance, what inferences can be made between the differences in sales performance of action game sales sold in the North American region versus European. Potenitally these similar sales regions could be used as a predictor in our bayesian model for yearly predictions.

# Obtains all genre sales in a given region, returns as key/val dictionary
# @param df The dataframe to query
# @param region The queried region
# @return dictionary of genres and sales values
def get_region_genre_sales(df, region):
    
    # Validate if df has a region column
    if region in df.columns:
        genre_sales = {}
        
        # Iterate through each unique genre and append all sales values
        for genre in df['Genre'].unique():
            genre_sales[genre] = df[df.Genre==genre][region]

        return genre_sales
    else:
        return None

# CITATION: The following non-parametric bootstrap resampling functions were created following
# .. Professor Stephen F. Elston's 2020-2021 Lecture 14 material and is credited as the original author. 

# Computes and plots a matrix of bootstrap distributions and estimates
# @param genre_sales A dictionary of genre sales key value pairs
# @param samples     The number of bootstrap samples to compute
# @param title       The title of the matrix plot
# @param x_label     The x axis label for each matrix plot
def plot_hist_matrix(genre_sales, samples, title, x_label):
    if genre_sales is None:
        raise Exception("Input matrix cannot be null") 

    n_rows = round(math.sqrt(len(genre_sales)))
    n_cols = round(len(genre_sales)/n_rows)

    # Create subplots
    figA, axesA = plt.subplots(nrows=n_rows, ncols=n_cols, figsize=(25,25))
    figB, axesB = plt.subplots(nrows=n_rows, ncols=n_cols, figsize=(25,25))
    # Iterate through dictionary of genre sales
    for i, genre in enumerate(genre_sales):
        axA = axesA[i//n_cols, i%n_cols]
        axB = axesB[i//n_cols, i%n_cols]
        
        # Compute a new bootstrap resample with n resamples
        bootstrap_mean_estimate, boot_means = bootstrap_mean(genre_sales[genre], samples)
        
        sm.qqplot(pd.Series(boot_means), fit=True, line="45", ax=axB)
        axB.set_title(genre + title)
        
        
        sns.histplot(boot_means, kde=True, ax=axA)
        axA.axvline(x=bootstrap_mean_estimate, color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=4)
    
        axA.set_xlabel(x_label)
        axA.set_title(genre + title)

    plt.show()

# Computes a resample of n samples for a genre's sales, returning the bootstrap mean
# @param genre_sales The sales values for the given region's genre
# @param samples     The number of samples to compute
# @return            A tuple containing the resamples and bootstrap estimate
def bootstrap_mean(genre_sales, samples):
    resamples = []
    
    # Append the resamples and compute the mean
    for i in range(samples):
        # Randomly sample n times with replacement
        resamples.append(np.mean(nr.choice(genre_sales, size=len(genre_sales), replace=True)))
        
        # Continuously recompute the bootstrap estimate
        mean_estimate = np.mean(resamples)

    return (mean_estimate, resamples)

# CITATION: The following two-sample bootstrap resampling function was created following
# .. Professor Stephen F. Elston's 2020-2021 Lecture 14 material and is credited as the original author. 

# Compute a two-sample bootstrap point estimate of given genre region's sales
# @param sample_A  The first of two samples to compute
# @param sample_B  The second of two samples to compute
# @param n_samples The number of bootstrap samples to compute
def two_sample_bootstrap_mean(sample_A, sample_B, n_samples):
    resamples = []
    # Append the resamples and compute the mean
    for i in range(n_samples):
        # independantly perform random sample n times with replacement
        sample_A_boots = np.mean(nr.choice(sample_A, size=len(sample_A), replace=True))
        sample_B_boots = np.mean(nr.choice(sample_B, size=len(sample_B), replace=True))
        resamples.append((sample_A_boots - sample_B_boots))
        
    # Recompute the bootstrap estimate
    mean_estimate = np.mean(resamples)

    return (mean_estimate, resamples)

def plot_two_sample_boot(sample_A, sample_B, samples, title, x_label):
    if sample_A is None or sample_B is None:
        raise Exception("Input matrix cannot be null") 
    
    for key in sample_A.keys():
        if key not in sample_B.keys():
            raise Exception("Input matricies cannot be differ in columns") 

    
    n_rows = round(math.sqrt(len(sample_A)))
    n_cols = round(len(sample_A)/n_rows)

    # Create subplots
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=n_rows, ncols=n_cols, figsize=(25,25))

    # Iterate through dictionary of genre sales
    for i, genre in enumerate(sample_A):
        ax = axes[i//n_cols, i%n_cols]
        
        # Compute a new bootstrap resample with n resamples
        two_bootstrap_mean, two_boot_means = two_sample_bootstrap_mean(sample_A[genre], sample_B[genre], samples)
        
        sns.histplot(two_boot_means, kde=True, ax=ax)
        ax.axvline(x=two_bootstrap_mean, color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=4)
    
    plt.show()

Compute the cognostics of profitable gaming genres irrespective of region.¶

Computing the cognostics of profitable gaming genres sheds light on an interesting discovery. Despite an initial assumption that the analysis of the top 4 growing genres in each region would each showcase growing trends, it is only the final "Other" sales region which features positive trending sales in the top four genres. This provides a valuable insight into the what I believe are current and future market growth trends for the industry. To begin, let us compare the results from each sales region. Despite one or two growing game trends in the North America, European and Japanese sales regions, each region typically features decreasing genres growth within their respective market. A closer inspection of sales within each region highlights a noticeable difference in magnitude of growth. Take for instance the comparison between shooter sales in North America versus "Other" (presumably a combination of South American, Middle Eastern and Oceania regions). Here we can see that North American Shooter titles feature significantly greater sales values when compared to those sold in "Other". However, North American Shooter sales appear to have reached a plateau, indicating a possible market stagnation. This insight is not shared with the "Other" region, which features rapid sales growth of the shooter genre within the same time period. I believe this phenomenia is the result of two factors. First, regions featured within "Other_Sales" may predominately feature gamers who utilize mobile devices. With greater access and afforability of smartphone devices, a new demographic of gamers has increasing become apparent to developers and publishers. According to a 2019 market analysis of the global games industry, mobile game sales accounted for 45% of globgal game sales [7]. Further research in this domain should confirm if the growth of gamers leveraging mobile devices coinsides with the growth in sales featured in the "Other_Sales" region. Should this insight prove valid, this should reinforce to publishers the importance of captializing on the growth of the mobile game market.

The second factor which I believe plays critical component in better understanding per-region genre growth, is market maturity of The North American, European and Japanese sales region, particularly when compared to those within "Other_Sales". The relatively slow growth of sales within these mature markets likely highlights both the increasingly competitive nature of the games industry. Furthermore, the sales trend of the shooter genre in North America likely underscores the oversaturation of Shooter-based titles in the region.

# Compute the cognostics of the top 4 fastest selling game genres for each geographic region

# Following chapter 6, create intercept column in dataframe for linear reg. model
vgsales.loc[:,'intercept'] = [1.0] * vgsales.shape[0]


# Iterates over all sales regions, returns dict of genre sales slopes
# @param df      The dataframe to query
# @param column  The specified column to compute slopes
# @param regions The unique sales regions to iterate over
# @return        Dictionary of region/genre sale slopes key-value pairs
def get_region_slopes (df, column, regions):
    sales_slopes = {}
    
    for region in regions:
        slopes = []
        genres = []
        intercepts = []
        
        # CITATION: The following cognostic computation algorithm was created following
        # .. Professor Stephen F. Elston's 2020-2021 Lecture 6 material and is credited as the original author. 
        for entry in df[column].unique():
            temp = df.loc[df[column] == entry]
            
            mean_sales = np.mean(temp[region])
            temp.loc[:,region] = np.subtract(temp[region], mean_sales)
            
            std_sales = np.std(temp[region])
            temp.loc[:,region] = np.divide(temp[region], std_sales)

            temp_OLS = sm.OLS(temp[region],temp[['intercept','Year']]).fit()
            
            slopes.append(temp_OLS.params.Year)
            intercepts.append(temp_OLS.params.intercept)
            genres.append(entry)
        
        slopes_df = pd.DataFrame({'slopes':slopes,'intercept_coef':intercepts,'genres':genres})
        slopes_df.sort_values(by='slopes', ascending=False, inplace=True)
        slopes_df.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True)
        
        sales_slopes[region] = slopes_df

    return sales_slopes

region_slopes = get_region_slopes (vgsales, 'Genre', sales_groups)

def plot_trends(df, trend, region, title='', xlims=[1980.5, 2017.5], ylims=[None, None]):
    g = sns.FacetGrid(df, col='Genre', height=5, col_order=trend)

    g.set(xlim=(xlims[0],xlims[1]))
    g.set(ylim=(ylims[0], ylims[1]))
    g.fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.7)
    g.fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=20)
    plt.show()


# Iterate over dict of slopes, plot n number of plots
# @param df     The dataframe to query
# @param slopes A dictionary of region slope key value pairs
# @param rng    The n number of slopes to compute
def display_sales_growth(df, slopes, rng=(0,9)):
    for region, slope in slopes.items():
        growth = slope.loc[rng[0]:rng[1], 'genres']
        title = (str(rng[1]+1) + ' Fastest growing genres in ' + region)
        ymax = np.round(df[region].mean()*10,1)
        plot_trends(vgsales, growth, region, title, ylims=[0,ymax])

display_sales_growth(vgsales, region_slopes, rng=(0,3))

Projecting game sales with Bayesian Modelling¶

The ability to project and forcast future game sales is a critical component in the sucessful publication of a new titles. Bayesian modelling offers us the ability to fullfill exactly that requirement. Understanding projected sales distributions from a given region and time frame, requires a prior distribution computed from the previous year sales data from a sister region. As previously highlighted in the exploratory data analysis, the dataset provides entries for region and genre game sales dating back to 1980. However, the number of titles (particularly those who have met the threshold set for finacial success) are limited in count. To address this issue, the distribution range is extended to a five year period. By expanding the window of years to include we enable more information to be recorded for the given distribution.

Let us begin with the desire to understand projected action game sales data in the European region between 1996-2000. Here we leverage the known action game sales data between 1990-1995 from the North American sales region, this data will act as the model prior. The North American Sales region was selected specifically for the two regions similarities in consumer purchase habits. Using this information as the foundation for the prior, a posterior distribution must be computed for a given genre being a comercial success. Commerical success is defined as a game that recieves a minimum of 1 million copies sold. To achieve this binary categorization of sales values requires a one-hot-encoding of region sales, followed by a stratified sample from each region subdivided into genre to evaluate the accuracy of the posterior.

Following the successful enccoding of each genre's sales within their respective geographic region, we are now presented with the critical task of identifying a prior distribution for our Bayesian model. However, notice the relatively few number of queried results, as well as the small number of classifications of successful game sales. Despite the wide diversity of title entries in the dataset, the data still falls victim to the historical trends of game sales in their given year. Specifically, the number of titles for a given genre released earlier in the dataset will be fewer than those released presently, as previously demonstrated by the growth of genres in each given region.

The figure below showcases this issue. Having queried for game sales in a five year window during the early 90s, we see that action genre titles account for the smallest segment of titles released during that window. A quick glance indicates the sports genre features the largest number of entries for this year range. However, upon closer inspection, it appears that this genre features no titles that qualify as our definition of a commercial success. Instead, it appears that platform titles offer the best balance between maximizing title count and sale success count. In order to maximize the size of our prior distribution, our model will instead leverage platform genre sales rather than action titles.

With the limited sample size of game sales, the prior distribution will be computed using the known likelihood of platform sales between 1990-1995 multiplied by a beta conjugate distribution. A beta conjugate was selected given the binomial nature of the commerical success/failure encoding previous computed.

# CITATION: The following distribution plot functions were created following
# .. Professor Stephen F. Elston's 2020-2021 Lecture 7 material and is credited as the original author.

# Plots given distribution over sample space
# @param title        Title of the plot
# @param xlable       X axis lable for the plot
# @param distribution Distribution to be plotted
# @param p            Sample space
def plot_distribution (title, xlabel, distribution, p):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 4))
    ax.plot(p, distribution)
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    ax.set_ylabel('Distribution')
    plt.show()
    
# Resamples and Plots given density of samples in distribution
# @param title        Title of the plot
# @param xlable       X axis lable for the plot
# @param size         Number of desired resamples
# @param distribution Distribution to be plotted
# @param p            Sample space
def plot_density(title, xlabel, size, p, distribution):
    resamples = np.random.choice(p, size=size, p=distribution)
    
    plt.hist(resamples, bins=20, density=True)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.ylabel('Density')
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.show()
In [147]:
# Computes the likelihhood of a given distribution
# @param p Sample count
# @param k Success count
# @param n Param shape
# @return  Distribution likelihood
def compute_likelihood(p, k, n):
    # Given the two possible categorizations for succesfful sales (either reaching 1mill or not), 
    # .. leverage binomal likelihood
    return scipy.stats.binom.pmf(k, n, p)

# Computes a Beta distribution of a given distribution
# @param p Sample count
# @param k Pseudo success count
# @param k Pseudo failure count
# @param n Param shape
# @return  Probability distribution
def compute_beta_prior(p, a, b, n):
    pp = scipy.stats.beta.pdf(p, a, b)/n
    return pp

# Computes a posterior using prior and likelihood
# @param prior The prior distribution
# @param like  The likelihood of the prior distribution
# @return      Normalized Posterior distribution
def compute_posterior(prior, like):
    
    # CITATION: The following posterior calcuation algorithm was created following
    # .. Professor Stephen F. Elston's 2020-2021 Lecture 7 material
    posterior = np.multiply(prior, like)
    return np.divide(posterior, posterior.sum())

This evidence should underscore the rapid growth in popularity of video games in western markets.

Conclusion¶

This report analyized the purchasing patterns of video game consumers throughout history and showcased the use of a bayesian linear model to predict historical game sales. The report leveraged the 'Video Game Sales' dataset, which contained historical video games sales with more than 100,000 copies solid. An initial exporatory data analysis highlighted how preferences of gamers vary by region, with video game titles within the action game genre accounting for the largest group in the western sales regions. Further exploration of the dataset revealed additional nuance in perferencial difference between gamers across the world. Specifically, Japanese players vastly prefer role-playing style games, running contrary to Western markets. Desipite the differences between western and asian sales markets, North American and European markets shared a number of similarties. These simiarites included the dominance of action, shooter and sports titles sold in both regions. As such, the regional similarities of consumer purchasing habits in western markets provided a foundation as a predictor in the bayesian analysis of historical sales predictions. This provided a confirmation that a predictive model to simulate game sales based on genre may prove useful to publishers, who may wish to better understand the regional differences in consumer purchasing habits. The paper presented readers with a basyian model simulate to historical, genre specific, game sales. The intent of this model is to better inform developers and publishers on past consumer and market trends. Results from the bayesian model indicated that titles published during the earlier infancy of the games industry were more likely to generate higher volumn sales on average, when compared to titles sold in the late 2000's. However, the model results featured bias through a significant difference in yearly sales data, as well as a cross-comparison between non-similar game genres. Furthermore, the bayesian models presented solely compared Western sales markets. Future research should attempt to compare and contrast genre sales performance between Asian and Western audiences.
